sentences: Dominique Rijpma van Hulst (Dutch pronunciation: [doːmiˈnik rɛi̯pmaː fɑn ɦʏlst]; born 7 September 1981) is a Dutch singer and actress known by her stage name Do.
Dominique Rijpma van Hulst was born in 1981 in Valkenswaard, Netherlands.
Do's self-titled debut, Do, was released in 2004, and reached No. 3 in the Netherlands.
A specially recorded version of "Angel by My Side" was used as the title song for the 2004 Dutch film "Ellis in Glamourland".
Do's second album, Follow Me was released in the Netherlands on 19 June 2006.
The song was written by Bryan Adams and had already been recorded by Melanie C in 1999.
In 2006, Do did a tour called Follow Me theater tour.
It was released in February 2007.
On 20 December 2009, Do premiered a new song, called "Nobody But Me", which was said to be off her upcoming album.
In 2010, Dominique Rijpma van Hulst released an LP version of "Zingen in het Donker".
On 7 July 2007 Do married Marc Verschoor in Barcelona.
The couple divorced in 2010 but reconciled in 2012.
The couple divorced in 2010 but reconciled in 2012.
She gave birth to a son on 2 January 2014.
Dominique Rijpma van Hulst stated the album was going to be released around March 2010; however, it has yet to be released.
From November 2007 to March 2008 Do starred in Assepoester, a Dutch version of Cinderella, as the title character.
She is best known for singing the vocals of "Heaven," DJ Sammy's worldwide top 10 hit in 2002-2003, a cover of the 1980s hit of the same name by Bryan Adams.
The album received the golden status (40,000 copies) in the Netherlands just before Christmas.
To end the year, she recorded a Christmas song with Trijntje Oosterhuis on the order of Sky Radio.
It was called "Everyday Is Christmas".
The song, "Als Je Iets Kan Doen" (If You Can Do Something), reached No. 1 in the Netherlands and stayed there for several weeks.
The album debuted in the Dutch Megacharts Album Top 100 at No. 8 and peaked there for two weeks.
It stayed in the Top 40 for 9 weeks.
Do posed nude in, and was featured on the cover of, the January 2009 issue of the Dutch edition of Playboy.
